info.name: Nitrogen Developer API
info.description: Welcome to the Nitrogen API website! Here you will find detailed information about the various endpoints for the Nitrogen API. The Nitrogen API utilizes OAuth 2.0 with the authorization code flow. For more on OAuth 2.0 with authorization code, see [https://oauth.net/2/grant-types/authorization-code/](https://oauth.net/2/grant-types/authorization-code/) # Security Policy We take breaches of security very seriously at Nitrogen. If you have had a security breach in which any Nitrogen data or credentials may have been compromised, contact us immediately at [apisupport@nitrogenwealth.com](https://mailto:apisupport@nitrogenwealth.com). While the following is not meant to be an exhaustive list, below are some examples of what would constitute a security incident that could cause the temporary suspension or permanent termination of your API access. 1. Use of a non-test Nitrogen account with your test API credentials 2. Launching your solution to production without first passing Nitrogen's review 3. Launching your solution to production with your test API credentials 4. Insecurely handling or transmitting your OAuth client secret. There is NEVER a reason to send us your OAuth client secret outside of our API. 5. Insecurely handling or transmitting an OAuth auth code, access token, or refresh token. There is NEVER a reason to send us an auth code, access token, or refresh token outside of our API. 6. Insecurely implementing the Nitrogen API 7. Allowing one user to see another user’s data 8. Obtaining, storing, transmitting, or using the username and password of one of our customers Please consult your API agreement for further provisions. # API Access Access to the Nitrogen Developer API is by approval only. In order to do this, contact your account representative. Every request that your application sends to a Nitrogen API needs to be identified. Once you have obtained API credentials, you can connect to our API with an OAuth 2.0 access token in your request. # API Calls Nitrogen APIs utilize a RESTful design. This means that you use standard HTTP methods to retrieve and manipulate objects. The base url for Nitrogen APIs is [https://api2.riskalyze.com/](https://api2.riskalyze.com/). _Note:_ All requests to the API must be made via HTTPS protocol and include proper API credentials. ## Request Methods The Nitrogen APIs expose various endpoints for working with resources. Each endpoint supports one or more of the following HTTP request methods: GET: Used to retrieve an individual resource, a list of resources, or to search resources. POST: Used to create a new resource. PUT: Used to update a resource. DELETE: Used to remove a resource. ## Response Codes The table below describes the most common response codes that you will receive from a request. In addition to the status code, most responses will receive a body with a JSON structure that represents the results of a successful request or additional error information. 200: OK 201: Created - Resource was received and stored successfully 202: Accepted - Resource was received and stored for process at a later time 204: Resource was deleted successfully 400: Bad Request - Response body will contain more information 401: Unauthorized - Response will include the WWW-Authenticate header 403: Forbidden - The requested resource is not assigned to your API key 404: Not Found - The requested resource does not exist at this time 500: Internal Server Error - Something went wrong… try again later # Quota Calls to the API must made made in accordance with your API agreement. Please contact your account representative for additional details. # Data Formats At this time, all resources in the Nitrogen APIs are represented using JSON data formats. The details of each resource are documented in the appropriate API. Sometimes the actual resource returned by the API will vary slightly from the representation in that it may include additional properties. If any undocumented data is useful feel free to use it with the understanding that it could disappear at any time. If undocumented properties drive a compelling use case for your application, feel free to let us know and we will consider adding it to the API spec. # Displaying Risk Numbers We offer two methods of displaying Risk Numbers: **Download** our art kit **Generate** Risk Number images via CDN. Generating Risk Number images via our CDN is the **preferred method**. To generate a Risk Number image via our CDN you will need to use an img tag with a URL of the following format: `https://1dc018be4716da4aaa18-5d73971c6ce0cd6d739efc4134c4b48a.ssl.cf2.rackcdn.com/v2/[TYPE]/[SIZE]/r[RISK NUMBER].[file extension (png or svg)]` We offer the following types: | Type | Description | Example | | --- | --- | --- | | standard | Risk Number with no special formatting. This would be used for a Client Risk Number | | | portfolio | Risk Number formatted for displaying a portfolio Risk Number | | We offer the following sizes, in pixels: 60, 90, 180, 360, and 1000. We also offer the graphics in the svg format. To get an svg, use svg for the size. Risk Numbers can be 1 through 99. Sending a Risk Number of 0 will return a faded question mark for an unknown Risk Number Example (png): [https://1dc018be4716da4aaa18-5d73971c6ce0cd6d739efc4134c4b48a.ssl.cf2.rackcdn.com/v2/standard/360/r59.png](https://1dc018be4716da4aaa18-5d73971c6ce0cd6d739efc4134c4b48a.ssl.cf2.rackcdn.com/v2/standard/360/r59.png) Example (svg): [https://1dc018be4716da4aaa18-5d73971c6ce0cd6d739efc4134c4b48a.ssl.cf2.rackcdn.com/v2/standard/svg/r59.svg](https://1dc018be4716da4aaa18-5d73971c6ce0cd6d739efc4134c4b48a.ssl.cf2.rackcdn.com/v2/standard/svg/r59.svg)

request.description:
Obtaining an auth code for an advisor's account is the first step in the process. An auth code will allow you to retrieve an access token and a refresh token.  
Access tokens are valid for 1 hour and are used to access the Nitrogen API.  
Refresh tokens are valid for 1 use or 90 days, whichever comes first.

redirect_uri may be passed to override the default redirect URI. Passing in a redirect_uri that matches the default redirect URI’s domain will override the default redirect URI. For example, if the default redirect URI is [https://www.example.com/response](https://www.example.com/response), passing in [https://www.example.com/response2](https://www.example.com/response2) or [https://response.example.com/override](https://response.example.com/override) will work. Passing in [https://www.example2.com/response](https://www.example2.com/response) will not work. Querystring parameters may be passed.

This call should be made in the user's browser. The user will be prompted to enter their Nitrogen credentials and approve the integration. They will then be automatically redirected back to your valid redirect URI which will include the querystring parameters of code and state. Code will be the auth code. State will be the state that you passed in the querystring as part of the call.

request.description: Exchange an auth code for an access token and a refresh token. The redirect_uri must match your default redirect_uri. Fuzzy matching is not supported with this call.
Exchange a refresh token for a new access token and a new refresh token. The redirect_uri must match your default redirect_uri. Fuzzy matching is not supported with this call.
An echo test to validate an access token.
Send Nitrogen an access token and get a response that tells you which user it belongs to.

Basic Single Sign On into Riskalyze directs the user to the Riskalyze Overview page.
Response is a hash. Append hash to https://pro.riskalyze.com/connect/ to launch Riskalyze.

Contextual Single Sign On directs the user to a specific Client, Portfolio, Questionnaire, or Retirement Map in Riskalyze.
Request is the same as Basic SSO.
Response is a hash. 
Append hash and a query string parameter to https://pro.riskalyze.com/connect/ to launch Riskalyze.
Only one query string parameter may be passed at a time.

Completed link should follow this format: https://pro.riskalyze.com/connect/<hash>?tc=1234567

Available Parameters:

| Key | Value            |
|----|----------------------------------|
| tc | a Client ID |
| tp | a Portfolio ID          |
| tq | a Risk Questionnaire ID | 
| tr | a Retirement Map ID     |

Returns a list of all clients visible to the user, including clients shared from other users.

For a list of all clients _owned_ by the user, excluding shared clients, append ?no_share=1.

Learn more about Riskalyze client sharing: [https://kb.riskalyze.com/hc/en-us/articles/115009224707-Data-Sharing](https://kb.riskalyze.com/hc/en-us/articles/115009224707-Data-Sharing)

request.description:
Use the Client ID to get a client's Name, Email, Risk Number, and a list of related objects. 

**TIP:** GET Client can be used to sync Client Risk Number, Current Portfolio Risk Number, and Proposal Risk Number in once call. Search the GET Client response for `latest_current_portfolio` and `latest_proposed_portfolio`. Then parse client[i].portfolios for the Risk Number associated with those portfolio IDs.

Allowed symbols include: `@` `_` `-` `.`
The `+` symbol will produce no search results. Submit a partial string to match instead.

request.description:
Add a new account to a model or client portfolio.

**id** | _string_ | Required. The ID of the portfolio to update.

**client_id** | _string_ | Required. The client_id the portfolio is linked to.

**name** | _string_ | Required. The name of the portfolio.

**type** | _string_ | Required. Accepted values are PROPOSAL and `ACTIVE`.

To mark an allocation as cash without a specific ticker symbol, set accounts.allocations.settings.shortname to 1000000000. This is a unique, internal identifier for cash in Riskalyze.

For portfolios, you may pass a property of **ephemeral_id** at the account level with each new account. This id will be returned with the account in the response. This can help in matching our account ids with your account ids. NOTE: ephemeral_id is not saved and will not be available in future responses.

request.description:
Specify a preferred proxy in case an investment is unrecognized by Riskalyze. You will need the Riskalyze Security ID of the preferred proxy you want to use. See the example response for a list of common proxies and their Riskalyze Security IDs.

Users can override preferred proxies by editing the portfolio inside of Riskalyze. User-set proxies take precedence over preferred proxies in API requests.

**id** | _string_ | Required. The ID of the portfolio to update.

**client_id** | _string_ | Required. The client_id the portfolio is linked to.

**name** | _string_ | Required. The name of the portfolio.

**type** | _string_ | Required. Accepted values are TARGET and ACTIVE.

**account.id**  |  _string_  |  Required. The Riskalyze account.id of the account to be updated. Note: If you are adding a new account, do not include `account.id`.


To mark an allocation as cash without a specific ticker symbol, set accounts.allocations.settings.shortname to 1000000000. This is a unique, internal identifier for cash in Riskalyze.

request.description: Deleting models and protfolios

item.description:
Portfolios in Riskalyze are defined by their relationship with the Client object. Proposal and Active portfolios are displayed as "Proposed Portfolios" and "Current Portfolios" to Riskalyze users. Models are template portfolios which may be added to other portfolios as sleeves.

Use the attributes **type** and **status** to understand and define portfolios.

### Models

Portfolios not associated with a client. Changes made to the Model Portfolio will automatically be reflected in all Client Portfolios where that model is used. Models do not use "status"-- it will always show _null_ and should not be specified when creating a new model.

**type: "MODEL"**  
An active Model ready to be used in client portfolios.

**type: "DEVELOPMENT"**  
A draft Model, visible to the user, but not deployable in client portfolios.

### Portfolios

One client can have multiple portfolios of various types and statuses. Status is important when displaying portfolios in your integration. Treat portfolio(s) with status: " " as the most current, or offer the user the ability to select the portfolio they wish to reflect in your system.

**type: "PROPOSAL"**  
A Proposed Portfolio. Should represent proposed future state of the client's investments. There can be multiple proposal portfolios for a client.

**type: “ACTIVE”**  
A Current Portfolio. Should always reflect the actual current holdings of a client.

**status: " "**  
Indicates this is the working version of a `PROPOSAL` or `ACTIVE` portfolio.

**status: "archived"**  
Indicates this is a past version of a `PROPOSAL` or `ACTIVE` portfolio. Advisors see archived portfolios in Riskalyze under the "Archived" heading in portfolio lists.

request.description:
Creates a questionnaire. See the [Riskalyze Knowledge Base](https://kb.riskalyze.com/hc/en-us/articles/115007198387-Capturing-a-Risk-Number#approaches "Risk Number Approaches") for information on how advisors use different types of questionnaires with clients. 

**client_id** | _string_ | Required. The ID of the client the questionnaire is for.

**type** | _string_ | Required. Accepted values: `next_gen`, `simple`, `detailed`. Default is `simple`.

**ai** | _number_ | Optional. The Amount Invested. If not specified, the user will set Amount Invested when completing the questionnaire.
Removes an existing Risk Questionnaire.

item.description:
A Questionnaire is represented in the Riskalyze API as the JSON data structure shown below. This representation is the superset of properties that a Questionnaire can contain.

    "advisor_id": {string},

}```

request.description: Create a retirement map.

item.name: Reports

query.description: The start date for the reports (format: YYYY-MM-DD). UTC timezone
The end date for the reports (format: YYYY-MM-DD). UTC timezone
Optional. Default 1. The page number for pagination
Optional. Default 10. Max value 100. The number of reports per page
Optional. Default ASC. The order in which to sort the reports by creation date (ASC,DESC)

request.description: Retrieves a list of reports for a specific client using the provided `client_id` and additional query parameters. The advisor must have access to the client, or the client must have been shared with the advisor.

variable.description: Id returned by List reports endpoint

request.description: Fetches details of a specific report using its unique ID. The report content is returned as a Base64-encoded string.

item.description: This collection provides endpoints to access reports. It includes operations to list all available reports and fetch details of a specific report by its ID. Both endpoints require an OAuth 2.0 access token for secure authorization.
